T1  - Knowledge Transfer Through Inheritance: Spin-Out Generation, Development, and Survival
AU  - Agarwal, Rajshree
AU  - Echambadi, Raj
AU  - Franco, April M.
AU  - Sarkar, MB
Y1  - 2004/08/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/20159599
DO  - 10.5465/20159599
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 501
EP  - 522
VL  - 47
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We investigated how the knowledge capabilities of industry incumbents affected the generation, development, and performance of ?spin-outs? (entrepreneurial ventures of ex-employees). Analyses of 1977?97 data from the disk drive industry supported our hypothesis that incumbents with both strong technological and market pioneering know-how generate fewer spin-outs than firms with strength in only one of these areas. Also, an incumbent?s capabilities at the time of a spin-out?s founding positively affect the spin-out?s knowledge capabilities and its probability of survival.
AB  - We investigated how the knowledge capabilities of industry incumbents affected the generation, development, and performance of ?spin-outs? (entrepreneurial ventures of ex-employees). Analyses of 1977?97 data from the disk drive industry supported our hypothesis that incumbents with both strong technological and market pioneering know-how generate fewer spin-outs than firms with strength in only one of these areas. Also, an incumbent?s capabilities at the time of a spin-out?s founding positively affect the spin-out?s knowledge capabilities and its probability of survival.
