TY  - JOUR
T1  - When the Known Devil is better Than an Unknown God: An Empirical Study of the Antecedents and Consequences of Relay CEO Successions
AU  - Zhang, Yan
AU  - Rajagopalan, Nandini
Y1  - 2004/08/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/20159598
DO  - 10.5465/20159598
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 483
EP  - 500
VL  - 47
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Taking an organizational learning and adaptation perspective, we compared ?relay? CEO successions with nonrelay inside successions and outside successions. Data on 204 CEO successions between 1993 and 1998 in nondiversified U.S. manufacturing firms showed that the likelihood of relay succession was negatively associated with the number of internal candidates and positively associated with presuccession firm performance. We also found that relay successions led to better postsuccession firm performance, particularly at lower levels of presuccession firm performance and higher levels of postsuccession strategic and industry instability.
AB  - Taking an organizational learning and adaptation perspective, we compared ?relay? CEO successions with nonrelay inside successions and outside successions. Data on 204 CEO successions between 1993 and 1998 in nondiversified U.S. manufacturing firms showed that the likelihood of relay succession was negatively associated with the number of internal candidates and positively associated with presuccession firm performance. We also found that relay successions led to better postsuccession firm performance, particularly at lower levels of presuccession firm performance and higher levels of postsuccession strategic and industry instability.
